article.description: Amber Harris had 21 points and 10 rebounds and No. 6 Xavier shot a season-best 66 percent, handling Saint Louis 92-60 for its 12th straight victory on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Harris' double-double powers No. 6 Xavier to 12th straight win
article.linkText: Harris powers No. 6 Xavier to 12th straight win
article.story:
ST. LOUIS --  Xavier's front line came up big again.

Amber Harris and Ta'Shia Phillips combined to make 17 of 20 shots, scored 41 points and totaled 17 rebounds in a 92-60 romp over Saint Louis on Wednesday night.

The sixth-ranked Musketeers shot a season-best 66 percent and won their 12th in a row.

"They're special players and we certainly knew we had an advantage around the basket," coach Kevin McGuff said. "I credit them for working as hard as they did."

The 6-foot-5 Harris shot 8 for 9 and had 21 points, 10 rebounds and two blocked shots for her 13th double double. The 6-6 Phillips was 9 for 11 and scored 20 points with seven rebounds.

The Musketeers (22-2, 10-0 Atlantic 10) have beaten half of their opponents by 20 or more points during the winning streak, which began on Jan. 5 against Missouri after consecutive losses to Duke and Stanford.

"So far, so good," Phillips said. "There's always things you can tweak and change to be a better team going into March. We're not quite there yet, but we'll get there in the next few weeks."

The four-time defending Atlantic 10 champions have won 26 straight regular-season conference games and easily topped their previous best shooting of 55.7 percent in the opener against South Carolina.

"When I watch them on film, they play hard when they want to play hard," Saint Louis coach Shimmy Gray-Miller said. "They're so balanced, inside and outside. I don't think it would be a stretch at all to see them in the Final Four."

Jacy Bradley had 13 points and reserve Ashley Hanley matched her career best with four 3-pointers and 12 points for Saint Louis (7-19, 1-10), which has lost six in a row by an average margin of 26 points and 12 of 13 overall.

The Billikens matched their season best with eight 3-pointers but faded after hitting their first five shots, three by Mallory Eggert, shooting 35.6 percent.

"We played a little bit out of our minds, outside of ourselves, and then we kind of came back to earth," Gray-Miller said. "We just wanted to compete and not back down, and I thought my kids did that."

Xavier was shooting better than 70 percent before McGuff emptied the bench.

"We just wanted to come out and have high intensity. I think we did that," Harris said. "It was not that hard to focus, we just kept working hard."

Saint Louis led 9-4 early but was 4 for 27 to end the first half while Xavier took a 46-22 lead. Harris had five points in an 11-0 run that put Xavier ahead 21-13 with just under 12 minutes left in the half.

Senior guard Lauren Woods, Saint Louis' leading scorer with a 10.3-point average, did not start and was scoreless in 15 minutes.

"She really has been kind of a no-show this whole year, so I've been relying on freshman and sophomores," Gray-Miller said. "She's not giving us what we need."
